---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import flowchartImage from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/Flowchart.png";
import ox1Image from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/ox_1.jpg";
import oxfamScreen1Image from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/oxfam-screen-1.jpg";
import oxfamScreen2Image from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/oxfam-screen-2.jpg";
import oxfamScreen3Image from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/oxfam-screen-3.jpg";
import tybScreen1Image from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/screens/tyb-1.png";
import tybScreen2Image from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/screens/cash-1.png";
import tybScreen3Image from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/screens/cash-3.png";
import tybScreen4Image from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/screens/ox_2.png";
import tybScreen5Image from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/screens/tyb-5.png";
import tybScreen6Image from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/screens/thanks.png";
import tybScreen7Image from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/screens/timeout.png";
import tybScreen8Image from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/screens/unwrapped-2.png";
import tybScreen9Image from "../../../images/tag-your-bag/screens/unwrapped-4.png";
---

<BaseLayout title="Tag Your Bag · Case Study">
  <section class="introduction">
    <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/home">Home</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span aria-current="page">Tag Your Bag</span>
    </nav>
    <h1 class="hero-title">
      Digitising Gift-aid registration across Oxfam's high-street stores<span
        class="flourish-period">.</span
      >
    </h1>
    <ul class="meta-list meta-list--casestudy meta-list--pills">
      <li>Oxfam <span style="text-transform:none">(via PXTech)</span></li>
    </ul>
    <div class="hero-wrapper">
      <section class="hero-lead">
        <p>
          <strong>
            Redesigning a fragile service interaction that was costing Oxfam
            significant revenue each year.</strong
          >
        </p>

        <p>
          Oxfam asked PXTech to explore whether redundant in-store POS hardware
          could be repurposed as self-service Gift Aid registration kiosks.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="card card--role card--compact card--transparent">
        <h2>Role</h2>
        <ul class="role-list">
          <li>Stakeholder liaison</li>
          <li>Process and flow design</li>
          <li>Interface and on-brand visual design</li>
          <li>Front-end implementation</li>
          <li>In-situ usability testing and validation</li>
        </ul>

        <ul class="tools-list">
          <li>
            <img
              class="tools-list__icon"
              src="/images/tools/sketch.png"
              alt="Sketch"
            />
          </li>
          <li>
            <img
              class="tools-list__icon"
              src="/images/tools/jira.png"
              alt="Jira"
            />
          </li>
          <li>
            <img
              class="tools-list__icon"
              src="/images/tools/photoshop.png"
              alt="Photoshop"
            />
          </li>
          <li>
            <img
              class="tools-list__icon"
              src="/images/tools/html.jpg"
              alt="HTML CSS"
            />
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Problem</h2>
    <p>
      Oxfam estimated it was missing out on around £1m per year due to
      incomplete or illegible Gift Aid forms.
    </p>
    <p>
      The existing process relied on handwritten forms that were later manually
      processed and transcribed. This created three core issues:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Lost revenue through incomplete or invalid registrations</li>
      <li>High administrative overhead</li>
      <li>Risk of non-compliance with legal requirements</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      At the same time, Oxfam had recently upgraded POS terminals across ~650 UK
      stores. The question was whether the old touchscreen units could be
      repurposed as self-service Gift Aid kiosks.
    </p>
    <p>
      The hardware proof of concept was in place. What was missing was a
      structured experience that people could navigate confidently and
      consistently.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Approach</h2>
    <p>
      When I joined the project, the content and legal copy were sitting in
      spreadsheets. The proposed flow felt fragmented and overly complex.
    </p>
    <p>
      Stakeholders initially leaned toward collecting additional information
      “just in case.” I made the case that every extra field could reduce
      completion rates and increase drop-off — directly undermining the revenue
      recovery goal.
    </p>
    <p>
      While working closely with stakeholders at Oxfam’s head office, I reframed
      the approach around a simple principle: <strong>
        collect only what is essential.
      </strong>
    </p>

    <h3>Key decisions</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Move eligibility and donation-type questions to the start</li>
      <li>Reduce required fields to the legal minimum</li>
      <li>Group contact details into clear, logical sections</li>
      <li>
        Structure the flow semantically rather than mirroring the spreadsheet
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Success also depended on buy-in from store volunteers, many of whom were
      non-technical and cautious about change.
    </p>
    <p>
      I requested that one of the 20 trial stores be local to our office,
      allowing me to spend time in-store observing, testing and building trust
      with staff and volunteers.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="image-row">
    <Image
      class="full-width-image"
      src={flowchartImage}
      alt="Tag Your Bag service flowchart"
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
  </section>
  <p class="image-row--caption">
    An accessible, 'stakeholder friendly' flowchart helped me get buy-in for a
    simplified linear approach.
  </p>

  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Build</h2>
    <p>
      With the flow agreed and legal requirements clarified, I designed firstly
      in Sketch, and then increasingly in the browser.
    </p>

    <h3>Constraints</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Low-resolution touchscreen hardware</li>
      <li>On-screen keyboard reducing usable content area to ~1024 × 500</li>
      <li>Shared in-store WiFi with unstable connectivity</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Design decisions</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Larger form fields and scaled typography for legibility</li>
      <li>Clear step emphasis to reinforce progress</li>
      <li>Strong visual hierarchy optimised for touch interaction</li>
      <li>Branded but simplified colour palette</li>
      <li>
        Carefully chosen start and end imagery for reassurance and clarity
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      I created a webfont variation of the brand typeface and iterated layouts
      live in-browser to work within the tight screen constraints.
    </p>
    <p>
      As testing revealed connectivity issues across stores, we introduced
      clearer error messaging and built greater resilience into the experience
      so staff could recover quickly when WiFi dropped.
    </p>
  </section>
  <section class="image-row">
    <Image
      src={ox1Image}
      alt="Tag Your Bag kiosk screen"
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
  </section>
  <p class="image-row--caption">
    Usability testing happened in store with real donors and shop staff.
  </p>
  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Testing</h2>
    <p>Testing happened in context, with real donors and volunteers.</p>
    <p>
      Initial volunteer reactions were cautious. Rather than defend the design,
      I focused on explaining the purpose of the project — recovering lost
      charity income — and demonstrating how the kiosk reduced manual admin.
    </p>
    <p>That shift in framing helped adoption.</p>

    <h3>Findings</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>
        Volunteer confidence was fragile; unclear structure increased
        hesitation.
      </li>
      <li>Users needed clearer signalling of progress and completion.</li>
      <li>The Nectar integration point created uncertainty as to purpose.</li>
      <li>
        Store WiFi instability posed a risk to completion and operational
        confidence.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Being physically present in-store allowed me to observe hesitation,
      workarounds and environmental constraints in real time.
    </p>

    <h3>Response</h3>
    <p>
      I refined the flow to prioritise eligibility upfront, reduced supporting
      copy to essential guidance, and strengthened visual step progression to
      reinforce completion.
    </p>

    <p>
      I introduced clearer Nectar branding at the integration point and
      simplified language around data use to improve trust.
    </p>

    <p>
      Working with engineering, I built in connectivity safeguards and clearer
      recovery messaging to mitigate network instability.
    </p>

    <p>
      The revised design was validated through further live testing before full
      rollout.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="image-row image-row--3">
    <Image
      src={tybScreen4Image}
      alt="Tag Your Bag screen"
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
    <Image
      src={tybScreen1Image}
      alt="Tag Your Bag screen"
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
    <Image
      src={tybScreen8Image}
      alt=""
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
  </section>

  <section class="image-row image-row--3">
    <Image
      src={tybScreen9Image}
      alt=""
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />

    <Image
      src={tybScreen2Image}
      alt=""
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
    <Image
      src={tybScreen3Image}
      alt=""
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
  </section>
  <section class="image-row image-row--3">
    <Image
      src={tybScreen5Image}
      alt=""
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
    <Image
      src={tybScreen7Image}
      alt="Tag Your Bag screen"
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />

    <Image
      src={tybScreen6Image}
      alt=""
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
  </section>
  <p class="image-row--caption">
    Sample kiosk interface screens from the Tag Your Bag and cash donations
    flows.
  </p>

  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Impact</h2>
    <p>
      The trial proved viable and demonstrated a clear uplift in data quality.
      Following full rollout across approximately 650 UK stores, invalid Gift
      Aid registrations reduced by around 50%, contributing to the retention of
      an <strong>estimated £500k in previously lost annual income</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The kiosks went on to become a white-label solution available to charities
      nationwide.
    </p>

    <!-- <p>
        The project reinforced that reducing data collection increases clarity
        and completion, structural simplification matters more than visual
        polish, volunteer confidence is as important as donor usability, and
        real-world constraints such as unstable connectivity materially shape
        product success.
      </p> -->
  </section>

  <div class="image-row image-row--full image-row--3">
    <Image
      src={oxfamScreen1Image}
      alt="Tag Your Bag kiosk screen 1"
      style="height:auto; width:100%; display:block;"
      widths={[480, 768, 1024]}
      sizes="(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 50vw"
    />
    <Image
      src={oxfamScreen3Image}
      alt="Tag Your Bag kiosk screen 2"
      style="height:auto; width:100%; display:block;"
      widths={[480, 768, 1024]}
      sizes="(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 50vw"
    />
    <Image
      src={oxfamScreen2Image}
      alt="Tag Your Bag kiosk screen 2"
      style="height:auto; width:100%; display:block;"
      widths={[480, 768, 1024]}
      sizes="(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 50vw"
    />
  </div>
  <p class="image-row--caption">
    Kiosk spotted in an Oxfam store ~3 years after I completed the project.
    While the UI has evolved in line with branding, the principles I defined
    remain intact.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
